 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): perhaps a variant of   Corney  , a habitational name from Corney in Kirkham (Lancashire), with voicing of the initial consonant. Alternatively, a variant of <b>Cornall</b>, itself either a Lancashire variant of   Corney   (where <i>-all</i> and <i>-ell</i> are hypercorrect pronunciations of <i>Cornah</i>, <i>Corner</i>, and <i>Cornoe</i>, late pronunciations of <i>Corney</i>), or a variant of the Devon name   Cornwall  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Corney","meanings":["habitational name from Corney in Cumbria or Corney in Hertfordshire (now known as Corneybury), from Old English <i>corn</i> ‘grain’ or <i>corn</i>, a metathesized form of <i>cron</i>, <i>cran</i> ‘crane’ + <i>ēg</i> ‘island’. It seems possible, from the distribution of early forms, that it may also derive from a lost place in Lancashire. Alternatively, a habitational name from Corney (Lancashire), later named <i>Corneyrow</i>, now Corner Row or Cornoe in Greenhalgh (alias Greenall), in the parish of Kirkham. <i>Corney</i> was sometimes pronounced and spelled <i>Cornah</i>, <i>Corner</i>, <i>Cornall</i>, <i>Gorney</i>, and <i>Gornall</i>.","perhaps a shortened form of   Cornwall   or   Cornish  , or a metathesized form of   Croney  .","English:"]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705207,"age":10,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705208,"age":12,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705210,"age":25,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When John Gorball was born in 1575, in Wilby, Suffolk, England, his father, John Gorball, was 25 and his mother, Grace Tayler, was 25. He married Mary Christiana Filby on 20 April 1590, in Wilby, Suffolk, England. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. He died in 1615, in his hometown, at the age of 40."},"et":{"1575–1615":"1575–1615","1576–1620":"1576–1620","1592–1622":"1592–1622","1598–1667":"1598–1667","1550–1615":"1550–1615","1550–1639":"1550–1639","1550":"1550","1592":"1592","1667":"1667","1600":"1600","1622":"1622","1587":"1587","1598":"1598","1620":"1620","1576":"1576","1575":"1575","1585":"1585","Abt. 1598":"umbes 1598","20 April 1590":"20. aprill 1590","1639":"1639","1615":"1615","Wilby, Suffolk, England":"Wilby, Suffolk, England","Dennington, Suffolk, England":"Dennington, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wrentham, Suffolk, England":"Wrentham, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"1575–1615":"1575–1615","157